SIMPLE: welkin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Welkin
<hw>Wel"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>welken</ets>, <ets>welkene</ets>, <ets>welkne</ets>,
<ets>wolcne</ets>, <ets>weolcne</ets>, AS. <ets>wolcen</ets>, pl.
<ets>wolcnu</ets>, a cloud; akin to D. <ets>wolk</ets>, OFries.
<ets>wolken</ets>, OS. <ets>wolkan</ets>, G. <ets>wolke</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wolchan</ets>, and probably to G. <ets>welk</ets> withered, OHG.
<ets>welc</ets> moist, Russ. & OSlav. <ets>vlaga moisture</ets>, Lith.
<ets>vilgyti</ets> to moisten.]</ety> <def>The visible regions of the
air; the vault of heaven; the sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the <qex>welkne</qex> shoon the sterres lyght.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fair <qex>welkin</qex> foully overcast.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When storms the <qex>welkin</qex> rend.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Used adjectively by Shakespeare in the phase,
⟦ldquo⟧Your <xex>welkin</xex> eye,⟦rdquo⟧ with uncertain
meaning.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Well</ent>⟦br⟧
